5.4.2	Peak Hour Flow
Peak Hour Flow (PHF), also referred to as Peak Hourly Design Flow (PHDF), represents the maximum rate of wastewater flow expected to reach the WWTP or pass through any component of the collection system within a single hour (or sometimes a shorter, more instantaneous peak). This value is critical for the hydraulic design of many components of the sewer system, including pipe diameters, pump capacities, lift station wet well sizing, and the hydraulic capacity of various treatment plant units (for instance,  screens, grit chambers, primary clarifiers), to ensure they can handle these peak loads without overflowing, surcharging, or experiencing operational issues such as reduced treatment efficiency.
Based on an inspection of flow data from 2022 to 2024, the highest peak flows for Tekoa’s system on the dates listed in Table 5.3-3 below. These events occurred during, or shortly after, significant rainfall events, indicating a strong RDII component contributing to the peaks. 
 
